<paragraph blockId="10.[151,1436,152,476]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,326,338,364]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">Variation.</emphasis>
Two females in poor condition from north of the known range of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Timberlake" authorityYear="1954" box="[1124,1237,338,363]" class="Insecta" family="Andrenidae" genus="Perdita" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pallida">
<emphasis box="[1124,1237,338,363]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">P. pallida</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<collectingRegion box="[1255,1378,338,364]" country="United States of America" name="California" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">California</collectingRegion>
, San Bernardino Co., near Saratoga Springs; Davis collection) may represent this species. They differ by the presence of dark markings on the head. These include a stripe above the antennal socket connected with markings in the interocellar region, and markings on the vertex behind the eye.
</paragraph>
